<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ901231-0089</DOCNO><DOCID>901231-0089.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   Environmental Control   Says President to Quit</HL><DATE>12/31/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE 11</SO><CO>   WNEWS ECGI</CO><IN>POLLUTION CONTROL, WASTE MANAGEMENT SERVICES (POL)</IN><LP>   PENNSAUKEN, N.J. -- Environmental Control Group Inc. saidits president and chief executive, Brian R. Esher, plans toleave the company early next year and that it is looking fora successor.   Mr. Esher, 42 years old, joined the company in the fall of1989 as chief executive, when the company was posting losses.Last July, he assumed the additional duties of chairman,succeeding John Stoddard, who had held the position sinceearly 1989.</LP><TEXT>   Environmental Control, a solid hazardous-waste controlconcern and insurance company, had third-quarter net incomeof $483,000, or seven cents a share, on revenue of $15.1million.   Environmental Control recently named its chief financialofficer, Anthony J. Gurley, to the post of chief operatingofficer, with responsibility for daily planning andadministration of Environmental Control's subsidiaries.   In 1989, Environmental Control posted a loss of $5.7million, causing technical defaults under its bank lendingagreements. The technical defaults have been eliminated.   &quot;The company's balance sheet has been strengthened, and wehave had good relations with the banks,&quot; Mr. Esher said,adding that bank debt has been reduced to less than $5million, from nearly $16 million when he joined the company.</TEXT></DOC>